Thread:
  execute single unit of operation 
  java atleast have one thread (main thread)
example : file downloads and still able to scroll the web page

Why Multithreading?
Better CPU utilization
Faster execution (parallel tasks)
Responsive UI (especially in apps)
Handles multiple users (server-side apps)

Ways to Create Threads in Java:

1. Using "extend" Thread class
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread running...");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyThread t = new MyThread();
        t.start(); // starts new thread
    }
}
2. using "Implements" on Runnable interface
class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Runnable thread...");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Thread t = new Thread(new MyRunnable());
        t.start();
    }
}
Runnable interface is preffered since its allows multiple inheritance and better design separation

Thread Life Cycle:
    New → Thread created
    Runnable → Ready to run
    Running → Executing
    Blocked/Waiting → Waiting for resource
    Terminated → Finished execution

methods in Thread:
  start() - start the thread
  run() - execute the code
  sleep(ms) - pause the thread
  join - wait for other thread
  yield - give chances to other
  interrupt()- stop/blocking signals

Synchronization:
When multiple threads access shared data → Race Condition so we need Synchronization 
class Counter {
    int count = 0;
    synchronized void increment() {
        count++;
    }
}

Inter-Thread Communication - Used when threads depend on each other.
Methods:
  wait()
  notify()
  notifyAll()

Thread Pool (Executor Framework) 
Instead of creating many threads manually:
          import java.util.concurrent.*;
          ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(3);
          executor.submit(() -> {
              System.out.println("Task executed");
          });
          executor.shutdown();
benefits:
  reuse the threads
  controls no of threads
  better performance

Common Problems in Multithreading:
  1. race condition - multiple threads updates same data 
  2. deadlock - thread waiting for other thread foreever
  3. thread starvation - no cpu time to execute . priority thread execute . so low priority thread never executes

